    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ac1945c2_150639ac",
        "filename": "results/recorder/chromium/formats/common.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 60,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-09-12T02:05:56Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Curious --- why is this the case (that doing multiple Write() calls instead of Join()ing and doing one) is significantly more efficient?\n\n(IIUC the comments w.r.t. removing sortedKeys argument, we\u0027re already walking the variant def map twice --- once to created the merged variant def map, and once to get the keys)",
      "parentUuid": "92062ed7_80007b00",
      "revId": "9854702e2d0a7e4107d7597631bee278b574cd44",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "26759568_425d6bc6",
        "filename": "results/recorder/chromium/formats/common.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 60,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-09-13T00:01:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "probably not significantly, since number of pairs is small. \n\nI believe it is more canonical to make multiple Write calls. For example, https://godoc.org/hash#example-package--BinaryMarshaler example makes two Write calls instead of making one Write call with concatenated content. The reason is same for any io.Writer (note that hash.Hash is io.Writer). If we print multiple lines in stdout, we use multple Println calls, instead of one Println call with strings.Join.\n\nIf we make one Write call like this, we allocate a large string that includes all pairs. With multiple Write calls, we don\u0027t. \n\nit is not a big deal though",
      "parentUuid": "ac1945c2_150639ac",
      "revId": "9854702e2d0a7e4107d7597631bee278b574cd44",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "acf863a0_9d5eb7ea",
        "filename": "results/recorder/chromium/formats/common.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 60,
      "author": {
        "id": 1134874
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-09-17T01:15:26Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Oh, I\u0027m fine with doing the multiple writes, was just wondering; thanks for the explanation.\n\nSo, to confirm:\n+ We have a method of the variant type to generate a sorted list of keys given the input map, which allocates a vector for all the keys, and walks the input map (created from walking the input maps in sequence).\n+ We have a method of the variant type to generate the []string of key:val pairs [so that we can use that to generate a human-readable variant definition].\n+ We also use that here and loop through to write each key:val string separately into the hash.\n\nDoes that accurately address the comments above w.r.t. breaking out the body of this hashing/digest-creating function?",
      "parentUuid": "26759568_425d6bc6",
      "revId": "9854702e2d0a7e4107d7597631bee278b574cd44",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
